{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486705"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:42:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:42:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"159"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/159"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.02,0.2,0.48,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"159"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109316"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/159"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"159"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91680"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"134"},{"type":"tags","id":"350"},{"type":"tags","id":"459"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"1293"},{"type":"tags","id":"1412"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"860"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12396"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13075"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14546"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42007"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43785"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109316"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of burning epigastric pain. The pain has been progressively worsening and is most noticeable after meals and at night. Over the last week, he has had multiple episodes of black and tarry stools. He has been on dual antiplatelet therapy with aspirin and clopidogrel since a coronary angioplasty two months ago. He has also strained his back one week ago during gardening and has been taking ibuprofen for pain relief. He has no other significant medical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 124/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals mild epigastric tenderness without guarding or rebound. The rest of the examination is normal. His haemoglobin is 112 g/L (135-155). An urgent oesophagogastroscopy is performed, revealing a 1 cm clean-based ulcer in the antrum of the stomach with no active bleeding or visible vessels. Pantoprazole is commenced.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following management options is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cease antiplatelet therapy until repeat endoscopy","Cease antiplatelet therapy indefinitely","Change antiplatelet therapy to low molecular weight heparin","Continue antiplatelet therapy","Empirical treatment of Helicobacter pylori"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management for this patient is to \u003Cstrong\u003Econtinue antiplatelet therapy\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient has had a mild gastrointestinal bleeding event with no haemodynamic instability or need for blood transfusion, likely precipitated by the use of a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) in addition to dual antiplatelet therapy. The endoscopic findings of a clean-based ulcer without active bleeding or visible vessels indicate a low-risk ulcer. Although this does have a small risk of further bleeding, the thrombotic risk associated with discontinuing antiplatelet therapy in the context of recent coronary stenting is much greater. Even in cases of more severe or recurrent bleeding, bleeding risk must be carefully balanced against the risks of ceasing antiplatelet therapy: this may involve the brief cessation of antiplatelet agents, a shorter overall duration of dual antiplatelet therapy, or the use of a single antiplatelet agent, depending on the patient\u0027s specific risk profile and following close consultation between cardiology and gastroenterology teams. The use of pantoprazole (a proton pump inhibitor) will help with ulcer healing and reduce the risk of recurrent bleeding, as will avoiding the further use of NSAIDs such as ibuprofen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeasing antiplatelet therapy until repeat endoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eindefinitely\u003C/strong\u003E puts the patient at high risk of stent thrombosis, given his recent coronary angioplasty. This approach is too aggressive particularly given the low-risk endoscopic findings. As the ulcer is gastric, the patient should still be considered for a repeat endoscopy to confirm ulcer healing and exclude underlying malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanging antiplatelet therapy to low molecular weight heparin\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this scenario. This approach does not provide adequate protection against stent thrombosis and introduces unnecessary anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile testing for \u003Cem\u003EHelicobacter pylori\u003C/em\u003E and treating if present is an important part of peptic ulcer disease management, this should be performed after its confirmed diagnosis, especially in light of increasing issues with antibiotic resistance, and therefore commencing \u003Cstrong\u003Eempirical treatment of \u003Cem\u003EHelicobacter pylori \u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003Eis not appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Management of antiplatelet therapy in the context of gastrointestinal bleeding requires careful consideration of thrombotic and bleeding risks."],"references":["Sverden E, Markar SR, Argus L, et al. Acute upper gastrointestinal bleeding. BMJ 2018;363:k4023. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30361444/","Halvorsen S, Storey RF, Rocca B, Sibbing D, Ten Berg J, Grove EL. Management of antithrombotic therapy after bleeding in patients with coronary artery disease and/or atrial fibrillation: expert consensus paper of the European Society of Cardiology Working Group on Thrombosis. Eur Heart J. 2017 ;38(19):1455-1462. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1093/eurheartj/ehw454"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91680"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"159"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91680"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-19T21:22:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-19T21:22:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"159"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109316"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"at